Git is a distributed version control system (VCS) that helps manage and track changes in source code or any collection of files over time. 
It is widely used in software development to facilitate collaborationamong developers and maintain a historical record of changes made to the codebase.

GIT --
============
  Opensource
  Download GIT and implement git in org

GIT HUB:
=======================
  Usability
  rAISING Issues
  Reviewing the code
  Commenting
  project management

GIT Installation
=================
apt-get install git
git
git init ###### initialize empty git repo and .git directory will be created which is responsible for tracking the changes
git commands
=====================================================
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"

=====================
git status
git add filename
git commit
git commit -m "<message>"
git diff
git log
git reset -- hard commitId to go to expected patch of CI
git push origin main  # Push changes to the 'main' branch
git pull origin main
git fetch origin
git branch
git checkout -b <branch name new>

CLONE Vs FORK
=======================
Clone -- download the repository
Fork -- create the copy of the repository
